message: /* Etymology */  A revised version of my previously contested edit, with an emphasis on neutrality and reliability.

Undid the citation objection by user Utcursch. The author is clearly implying that Gurjara and Pratihara were two prominent clans of a larger group of tribes which strongly inferred their Kshatriya status, and became Rajputs. Please read carefully.
Undid revision 710890570 by [[Special:Contributions/DpkKumar34|DpkKumar34]] ([[User talk:DpkKumar34|talk]]) Read the post "'Gurjara' is not 'Gurjar' or 'Gujjar'? Yeah Right!" on Talk page.

Undid revision 700202922 by [[Special:Contributions/Kautilya3|Kautilya3]] ([[User talk:Kautilya3|talk]]) Gurjar is the proper spelling for Gujjar, as recently witnessed in international media during the Gurjar Agitation, its not a marginal view at all.
IMHO "tribes" is a better representation of Rajput and Gurjar than "groups".
I have expanded the information from the cited source, and have also fixed the reference's format for Wikipedia.
